  "title": "Concurrency & Family of Lines",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "title": "Family Of Lines",
      "conceptBody": "<h3>Family of lines</h3><p>Family means of a group of lines having a particular characteristic so, we can say</p><p>(i) Family of lines parallel to $ax+by+c=0$ is of the form $ax+by+k=0$</p><p>(ii) Family of lines perpendicular to $ax+by+c=0$ is of the form $bx-ay+k=0$</p><p>(iii) Family of lines through the point of intersection of the lines</p><p>$a x+b y+c=0$ (1)</p><p>and $a^{\\prime} x+b^{\\prime} y+c^{\\prime}=0$ (2)</p><p>can be written as $\\left( ax+by+c \\right)+\\lambda \\left( {a}'x+{b}'y+{c}' \\right)=0$</p><p>Family of lines parallel to $\\text{x}$-axis are of the form $\\text{y}=\\text{k}$, where $\\text{k}$ is any arbitrary real number. Family of lines perpendicular to $2\\text{x}-\\text{y}+4=0$ is $\\text{x}+2\\text{y}+\\text{k}=0$ since product of slopes has to be -1</p><p><strong>Q) Find the equation of straight line through $\\left( 2,3 \\right)$ and&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>(a) parallel to $4\\text{x}-3\\text{y}=10$&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>(b) perpendicular to $4\\text{x}-3\\text{y}=10$&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong>Solution:&nbsp;</strong></p><p>(a) From family of lines we know that any line parallel to $4x-3y=10$ can be written as</p><p>$4\\text{x}-3\\text{y}=\\text{k}$ (1)</p><p>and now it should pass through $\\left( 2,3 \\right)$ so putting this in (i) &amp; finding $\\text{k}$</p><p>$4\\left( 2 \\right)-3\\left( 3 \\right)=\\text{k }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\Rightarrow \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ k}=-1$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ equation of req. line is $4\\text{x}-3\\text{y}+1=0$</p><p>(b) family of lines perpendicular to $4\\text{x}-3\\text{y}=10$</p><p>$\\Rightarrow \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }3\\text{x}+4\\text{y}=\\text{k}$</p><p>putting $\\left( 2,3 \\right)$ in the equation to find $\\text{k}$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }3\\left( 2 \\right)+4\\left( 3 \\right)=\\text{k }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\Rightarrow \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ k}=18$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ Required equation is $3\\text{x}+4\\text{y}-18=0$</p><p>&nbsp;</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0ddccc03b9dcaf1afeccc"
    },
    {
      "title": "Concurrency",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Function for concurrency of straight lines&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>Two or more lines are concurrent if they pass through one common point.</p><p>Let the equation of 3 straight lines be</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} {} &amp; {{a}_{1}}x+{{b}_{1}}y+{{c}_{1}}=0 \\\\ {} &amp; {{a}_{2}}x+{{b}_{2}}y+{{c}_{2}}=0 \\\\ {} &amp; {{a}_{3}}x+{{b}_{3}}y+{{c}_{3}}=0 \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>Then the condition for these 3 lines to be concurrent</p><p>$\\left| \\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} {{a}_{1}} &amp; {{b}_{1}} &amp; {{c}_{1}} \\\\ {{a}_{2}} &amp; {{b}_{2}} &amp; {{c}_{2}} \\\\ {{a}_{3}} &amp; {{b}_{3}} &amp; {{c}_{3}} \\\\ \\end{array} \\right|=0$</p><p>If there exists l, m, n (not all zero at a time) such that</p><p>$\\text{l}\\left( {{\\text{a}}_{1}}\\text{x}+{{\\text{b}}_{1}}\\text{y}+{{\\text{c}}_{1}} \\right)+\\text{m}\\left( {{\\text{a}}_{2}}\\text{x}+{{\\text{b}}_{2}}\\text{y}+{{\\text{c}}_{2}} \\right)+\\text{n}\\left( {{\\text{a}}_{3}}\\text{x}+{{\\text{b}}_{3}}\\text{y}+{{\\text{c}}_{3}} \\right)=0$</p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" width=\"226\" height=\"146\"></p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0ddccc03b9dcaf1afeccd"
    }
